"""mkt-original: Exodus 19–21
Type: original
Book: exodus
Chapters: 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-exodus-19-21-fill.py

Ch 19: Sinai arrival — the eagle-wings speech (segullah, mamlekhet kohanim, goy qadosh),
  covenant proposal and acceptance, the theophany (qolot, beraqim, anan kaveid, shofar).
  Key terms: segullah (treasured possession), qadosh (holy), kabed.
Ch 20: The Decalogue — all Ten Commandments with key Hebrew lexical notes.
  Key terms: al panai (before my face), pesel (idol), El qanna, shav (emptiness),
  zachor (remember), kabed (honor), ratzach (murder vs. kill), chamad (covet).
Ch 21: The Book of the Covenant begins — slave laws, homicide, lex talionis, ox-goring.
  Key terms: mishpatim (ordinances), eved (slave), ratzach/harag, nefesh tachat nefesh,
  ayin tachat ayin.

Note: ch 20 v.2 already present (anochi YHWH eloheicha entry).
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"19": {
"1": "<p><strong>bachodesh hashlishi letset bnei Yisrael me'eretz Mitsrayim bayom hazeh ba'u midbar Sinai</strong>: 'In the third month after the children of Israel left Egypt, on that day they came to the Sinai wilderness.' The arrival at Sinai is dated precisely — the third month after the Exodus, with <em>bayom hazeh</em> (on this very day) marking it as a kairos moment. The journey from Egypt to Sinai is the journey from redemption to revelation: deliverance comes first, then the covenant that shapes the delivered community. Torah is given to the redeemed, not as the means of redemption.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>vayisu miRefidim vayavou midbar Sinai vayachanu bamidbar vayichan sham Yisrael neged hahar</strong>: 'They journeyed from Rephidim and came to the wilderness of Sinai and camped in the wilderness. Israel camped there before the mountain.' The precise itinerary — from Rephidim (where water was struck from the rock) to Sinai — frames the covenant-giving between provision (water) and revelation (Torah). The camp <em>neged hahar</em> (opposite/facing the mountain) positions Israel as the audience of the divine theophany that will fill the mountain.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>uMosheh alah el-haElohim vayiqra elav YHWH min-hahar lemor ko tomar leveit Yaakov vetageid livnei Yisrael</strong>: 'Moses went up to God, and YHWH called to him from the mountain, saying: Thus shall you say to the house of Jacob, and announce to the children of Israel.' The double designation — <em>beit Yaakov</em> (house of Jacob) and <em>bnei Yisrael</em> (children of Israel) — addresses the community in both its domestic (house) and national (Israel) dimensions. Moses as covenant mediator ascends to receive what he will bring down: the pattern of the prophet who meets God on behalf of the people.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>atem re'item asher asiti leMitsrayim va'essa etchem al-kanfei nesharim vabi etchem elay</strong> (<em>ʾattem rĕʾîtem ʾăšer ʿāśîtî lĕmiṣrāyim wāʾeśśāʾ ʾetḵem ʿal-kanpê nĕšārîm wāʾābîʾ ʾetḵem ʾēlay</em>): 'You have seen what I did to Egypt, how I carried you on eagles' wings and brought you to myself.' <em>Nesher</em> (H5404, eagle): the eagle's training flight — hovering over the nest, carrying the young on its wings (Deut 32:11) — is YHWH's self-image for the Exodus: not rescue to a destination but rescue to a person. <em>Vabi etchem elay</em> (I brought you to myself): the Exodus goal is not the Promised Land but YHWH himself. The land is where YHWH will dwell with his people; the destination is personal, not geographic.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>ve'atah eem shamoa tishme'u beqoli ushmartem et-beriti vihyitem li segullah mikol-haamim</strong> (<em>wĕʿattāh ʾim-šāmôaʿ tišmĕʿû bĕqōlî ûšĕmartem ʾet-bĕrîtî wihyitem lî sĕgullāh mikol-hāʿammîm</em>): 'Now if you truly obey my voice and keep my covenant, you shall be my treasured possession among all peoples.' <em>Shamoa tishme'u</em>: infinitive absolute + imperfect — truly, truly obey. <em>Segullah</em> (H5459, treasured possession/personal property): one of the most precious terms in the covenant vocabulary, used only 8 times in the OT (Deut 7:6; 14:2; 26:18; Ps 135:4; Eccl 2:8; Mal 3:17; 1 Chr 29:3). In Mesopotamian contexts, <em>segullu</em> refers to the king's personal treasury — the most prized possessions kept close. Israel among all nations is YHWH's personal treasure. <em>Ki-li kol-ha'aretz</em> (for all the earth is mine): the universality of YHWH's ownership makes the particularism of election more striking, not less — he chose Israel from what is entirely his to choose from.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>vatem tihyu li mamlekhet kohanim vegoy qadosh</strong> (<em>wĕʾattem tihyû-lî mamleket kōhănîm wĕgôy qādôš</em>): 'You shall be for me a kingdom of priests and a holy nation.' Two covenant titles. <em>Mamlekhet kohanim</em> (kingdom of priests): every Israelite has the priestly vocation of mediating between YHWH and the world — Israel's existence is a priestly existence of access to God and representation before God. <em>Goy qadosh</em> (holy nation): <em>qadosh</em> (H6918, holy/set apart) — the national identity is consecration, not merely ethnicity. Peter applies these exact titles to the church in 1 Pet 2:9: you are a chosen race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a people for his own possession — the Sinai covenant's description of Israel is fulfilled and extended to the church in Christ.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>vayavo Mosheh vayiqra leziqnei ha'am vayasem lifneihem et kol-hadevarim ha'eleh</strong>: 'Moses came and called the elders of the people and placed before them all these words.' The mediatorial role: Moses receives from YHWH (v.3-6) and presents to the elders (v.7-8) — the chain of revelation. <em>Vayasem lifneihem</em> (placed before them): the covenant proposal as a laying-out, a presentation for consideration — not an imposition but an invitation requiring response. The elders as representative leaders of the tribal community carry the covenant response.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vaya'anu kol-ha'am yachdav vayomeru kol asher diber YHWH na'aseh</strong> (<em>wayyaʿănû ḵol-hāʿām yaḥdāw wayyōmĕrû kol ʾăšer-dibber Yhwh naʿăśeh</em>): 'All the people answered together and said: All that YHWH has spoken we will do.' The covenant acceptance: <em>yachdav</em> (together/united) — the whole community in one voice. <em>Kol asher diber YHWH na'aseh</em>: all that YHWH has said we will do. The commitment precedes hearing the specific commandments — a promissory note on what has not yet been fully disclosed. Moses brings back the people's words to YHWH: covenant is bilateral, requiring the community's public engagement.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>vehineni ba eleicha be'av he'anan ba'avur yishma ha'am bedabri imach vegam becha ya'aminu le'olam</strong>: 'Behold I am coming to you in a thick cloud, so that the people may hear when I speak with you and may also believe in you forever.' The thick cloud (<em>av he'anan</em>) serves a double purpose: YHWH's majesty is veiled (the cloud prevents the consuming fire from destroying Israel) while his voice is audible (so the people can hear). The Sinai theophany gives both audio access (the voice) and visual distance (the cloud). Paul in 2 Cor 3:14 uses the Moses-veil as the image of what Christ removes for the believer.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>vekidashtam hayom umachar vechibesu simlotam</strong>: 'Consecrate them today and tomorrow, and let them wash their garments.' <em>Kidash</em> (H6942, consecrate/sanctify) — the active preparation for encountering the holy. The washing of garments is external preparation that signifies internal readiness: one approaches YHWH with intentional preparation, not casually. The two-day preparation period before the third day (v.11, 16) mirrors the preparation structures of other theophany narratives (Num 11:18; Josh 3:5 — consecrate yourselves for tomorrow YHWH will do wonders).</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>vehayu nechonim layom hashlishi ki bayom hashlishi yered YHWH le'einei kol-ha'am al-Har Sinai</strong>: 'And be ready for the third day, for on the third day YHWH will descend in the sight of all the people on Mount Sinai.' The third-day descent of YHWH — the same eschatological timing that structures Hosea's resurrection promise (Hos 6:2: after two days he will revive us; on the third day he will raise us up) and Christ's resurrection. The third day is the day of divine appearing after a period of waiting.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>vehigbalta et-ha'am saviv lemor hishamru lachem alot bahar unegoa beqatzehu</strong>: 'And you shall set limits for the people on all sides, saying: Take care not to go up into the mountain or touch its edge.' The boundary at the holy mountain — the cordoning off of the holy space — is the spatial expression of the holy/common distinction. YHWH's presence makes the mountain holy; unauthorized approach means death. The Levitical laws of sanctuary access codify this spatial holiness into Israel's ongoing worship structure.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>lo-tiga bo yad ki saqol yisaqel o yereh yiyareh im-behema im-ish lo yichyeh</strong>: 'No hand shall touch it; he shall be stoned or shot with arrows; whether beast or man, he shall not live.' The death-penalty for violating the boundary — the most severe possible consequence for unauthorized approach to the holy. The principle behind the boundary is not arbitrary exclusion but the protection of mortal life from what it cannot survive unaided. The incarnation is YHWH solving the access problem from the inside: the holy comes to humanity rather than requiring humanity to approach the holy.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>vayered Mosheh min-hahar el-ha'am vayekadesh et-ha'am vayechabesu simlotam</strong>: 'Moses came down from the mountain to the people and consecrated the people, and they washed their garments.' The vertical movement of Moses — descending from the divine encounter to serve the human community — is the mediatorial pattern. Down and up, YHWH and Israel, divine and human: Moses traverses this axis continually. The washing of garments is the physical enactment of the moral-spiritual preparation for covenant encounter.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>vayomer el-ha'am hyu nechonim lishloshet yamim al-tigashu el-isha</strong>: 'He said to the people: Be ready for the third day; do not approach a woman.' The abstention from sexual relations before the divine encounter is the preparation of total focus — not because sexuality is impure but because covenantal encounter with the holy claims the whole person's orientation. The sexual union creates its own deep intimacy; approaching the deepest covenant intimacy requires a focused reorientation.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>vayhi vaboker hashhlishi vayhi qolot uveraqim ve'anan kaveid al-hahar veqol shofar chazaq me'od</strong> (<em>wayhî babbōqer haššĕlîšî wayhî qōlôt ûbĕrāqîm wĕʿānān kābēd ʿal-hāhār wĕqōl šôpār ḥāzāq mĕʾōd</em>): 'On the morning of the third day there were thunders and lightnings, and a thick cloud on the mountain, and a very loud trumpet blast.' The classic theophany vocabulary: <em>qolot</em> (H6963, thunders/voices), <em>beraqim</em> (H1300, lightnings), <em>anan kaveid</em> (heavy/thick cloud), <em>qol shofar</em> (sound of the ram's horn). John sees the same phenomena around the throne in Revelation (Rev 4:5; 8:5; 11:19; 16:18) — the Sinai theophany language is transported into the eschatological throne-room. <em>Vayecheradhu kol-ha'am asher bamachane</em>: all the people in the camp trembled.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>vayotse Mosheh et-ha'am liqrat haElohim min-hamachane vayatyatzevu betachtit hahar</strong>: 'Moses brought out the people from the camp to meet God, and they stood at the foot of the mountain.' <em>Liqrat haElohim</em> (to meet God): the covenant encounter is a meeting — a personal meeting requiring both parties to be present. Israel stands at the foot of the mountain — the lowest point, at the greatest distance that still constitutes approach. The vertical distance between foot and summit expresses the ontological distance between creature and Creator that the Sinai covenant bridges through revelation.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>vehar Sinai ashan kulo mipnei asher yared alav YHWH ba'esh</strong> (<em>wĕhar sînay ʿāšan kullô mippĕnê ʾăšer yārad ʿālāyw Yhwh bāʾēš</em>): 'Mount Sinai was wrapped in smoke because YHWH descended on it in fire, and the smoke went up like the smoke of a kiln, and the whole mountain trembled greatly.' Fire as YHWH's medium — his holiness consuming what it touches. The kiln-smoke image links to the Abrahamic covenant ceremony (Gen 15:17 — a smoking fire pot and a flaming torch passed between the pieces). YHWH's fire is both destructive (to the covenant-breaker) and purifying (for the covenant-keeper).</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>vayhi qol hashofar holech vechazeq me'od Mosheh yedaber vehA'Elohim ya'anenu beqol</strong>: 'The sound of the trumpet grew louder and louder. Moses spoke, and God answered him in thunder/a voice.' The reciprocal dialogue at the mountain — Moses speaking, God answering — is the model of covenant communication. <em>Ya'anenu beqol</em> (answered him with a voice): YHWH's voice in response to Moses's voice. The Sinai dialogue establishes the principle of divine responsiveness: when the covenant mediator speaks, the covenant Lord answers.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vayered YHWH al-Har Sinai el-rosh hahar</strong>: 'YHWH descended to the top of Mount Sinai, to the summit of the mountain.' The descent of YHWH to the mountain's summit is the ultimate condescension in the OT — the infinite entering the finite, the divine touching the earthly. John 1:14 uses the same language of descent: the Word became flesh and dwelt among us — the same divine-descent pattern but now complete, personal, incarnational. The Sinai descent is the OT version of what Bethlehem fulfilled.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vayomer YHWH el-Mosheh red ha'ed ba'am pen-yihersu el-YHWH lir'ot</strong>: 'YHWH said to Moses: Go down and warn the people lest they break through to YHWH to look and many of them fall.' The danger of unauthorized access even from curiosity: the desire to see (lir'ot) YHWH directly is presented as potentially fatal for those not prepared. The holy requires mediation for those not able to sustain its direct weight. The veil Moses wears after Sinai (34:33-35) is the spatial extension of this protective mediation.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>vegam hakohanim hanegishtim el-YHWH yitkadoshu</strong>: 'Even the priests who approach YHWH must consecrate themselves lest YHWH break out against them.' <em>Yitkadoshu</em> (Hitpael of qadash — consecrate themselves): the reflexive is important — the priests must perform their own consecration before approaching. The divine holiness is not simply a danger to the unprepared but an active force that breaks out against unauthorized approach (<em>yifrots YHWH</em>). The Levitical consecration system is the institutionalized form of this protective preparation.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>vayomer Mosheh el-YHWH lo yuchal ha'am la'alot el-Har Sinai</strong>: 'Moses said to YHWH: the people cannot go up to Mount Sinai, for you yourself commanded us, Set limits around the mountain and sanctify it.' Moses restates the boundaries YHWH established — the covenant mediator understands and enforces the access rules. The boundaries are not YHWH's hostility but his protection: he established the limits precisely so Israel could survive near the mountain. Structure enables encounter; without limits, encounter destroys.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>vayomer elav YHWH lech-red ve'alita atah ve'Aharon imach vehakohanim veha'am al-yihersu la'alot el-YHWH</strong>: 'YHWH said to him: Go down, and come up — you and Aaron with you — but do not let the priests and the people break through to come up to YHWH.' The graduated access structure at Sinai: Moses alone to the summit, Aaron allowed partway, priests below, people at the boundary. This vertical structure of covenantal access is the prototype of the tabernacle's and temple's spatial arrangement: most holy place (high priest), holy place (priests), outer court (Israelites), outer boundary (Gentiles).</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>vayered Mosheh el-ha'am vayomer aleihem</strong>: 'So Moses went down to the people and told them.' Moses's descent to speak the divine word to the people — the final movement before the Decalogue is spoken directly by God (20:1-17). The mediatorial descent prepares Israel for direct divine speech. When YHWH does speak directly from the mountain, the people's terror (20:18-19) demonstrates why mediation is necessary: the people need the mediator to survive the direct divine word.</p>"
},
"20": {
"1": "<p><strong>vayedaber Elohim et kol-hadevarim ha'eleh lemor</strong> (<em>waydabbēr ʾĕlōhîm ʾēt kol-haddĕbārîm hāʾēlleh lēʾmōr</em>): 'God spoke all these words, saying.' The direct divine speech of the Decalogue is unique in the OT — YHWH speaking directly to the entire assembled people, not through a prophet. <em>Kol-hadevarim ha'eleh</em> (all these words): the Decalogue is presented as divine speech, not human legislation. The authority of the Ten Commandments derives entirely from their speaker, not from their reasonableness or social utility.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>lo yihyeh lecha elohim acherim al panai</strong> (<em>lōʾ yihyeh-lĕkā ʾĕlōhîm ʾăḥērîm ʿal-pānāy</em>): 'You shall have no other gods before my face.' <em>Al panai</em> (before my face/in my presence): the commandment is spatially framed — in YHWH's presence there is no room for other allegiances. The command is not primarily a philosophical monotheism but a covenant loyalty: YHWH's face defines the space of relationship, and in that space the exclusive claim holds. <em>Elohim acherim</em> (other gods): the commandment does not deny the existence of other supernatural powers but prohibits their veneration in YHWH's presence.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>lo ta'aseh lecha pesel vechol-temunah asher bashamayim mima'al</strong> (<em>lōʾ taʿăśeh-lĕkā pesel wĕḵol-tĕmûnāh ʾăšer baššāmāyim mimmaʿal</em>): 'You shall not make for yourself an image/idol or any likeness of what is in heaven above.' <em>Pesel</em> (H6459, idol/image): from <em>pasal</em> (to cut/chisel) — a carved representation. The prohibition covers all representations of the divine in material form: sky, earth, or sea. The rationale emerges from the Sinai theophany: Israel heard a voice but saw no form (Deut 4:12 — you heard a voice but saw no form). YHWH's invisibility is theologically determinative: to make an image is to assign a form to what has no form, to domesticate what is beyond representation.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>lo tishtachaveh lahem velo ta'avdem ki anochi YHWH Eloheicha El qanna</strong> (<em>lōʾ-ṯiŝtaḥăweh lāhem wĕlōʾ ṯoʿoḇdēm kî ʾānōkî Yhwh ʾĕlōhêkā ʾēl qannāʾ</em>): 'You shall not bow down to them or serve them, for I, YHWH your God, am a jealous God.' <em>El qanna</em> (H7072, jealous God): <em>qanna</em> from <em>qana</em> (H7065, be jealous/zealous) — used exclusively of YHWH in the OT (Exod 34:14; Deut 4:24; 5:9; 6:15; Josh 24:19; Nah 1:2). Divine jealousy is not pettiness but the passion of a covenant Lord who has committed himself exclusively to his people and therefore cannot tolerate their divided loyalty. The jealousy of YHWH corresponds to the covenant's exclusive demand: monogamy and monotheism have the same structure. <em>Poked avon avot al-banim</em>: visiting the iniquity of the fathers on the children — the generational transmission of covenant violation (not arbitrary punishment but the natural consequence of covenantal patterns passing down).</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>ve'oseh chesed la'alafim le'ohavai uleshomrei mitzvotai</strong>: 'Showing steadfast love to thousands of those who love me and keep my commandments.' The asymmetry: iniquity to the third and fourth generation; <em>chesed</em> (H2617, steadfast love/covenant faithfulness) to <em>alafim</em> (thousands of generations). The divine mercy vastly exceeds the divine judgment in scope. The judgment extends three or four generations; the chesed extends to thousands. YHWH's primary orientation is mercy, not wrath; judgment is the reluctant instrument, love is the determinative character.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>lo tissa et-shem YHWH Eloheicha lashav</strong> (<em>lōʾ tiśśāʾ ʾet-šēm Yhwh ʾĕlōhêkā laššāwĕʾ</em>): 'You shall not lift/bear the name of YHWH your God for emptiness/vanity.' <em>Tissa</em> (H5375, lift/carry/bear): the verb is not about swearing but bearing — the name of YHWH is something carried. <em>Shav</em> (H7723, emptiness/vanity/worthlessness): not merely false oaths but any use of the divine name for trivial, empty, or purposeless ends. To bear the divine name (as Israel does as a covenant people) for emptiness is to misuse the covenant identity — whether in false oaths, magic, manipulation, or casual irreverence. The commandment protects the weight of the divine name.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>zachor et-yom haShabbat lekadsho</strong> (<em>zāḵôr ʾet-yôm haššabbāt lĕqaddĕšô</em>): 'Remember the Sabbath day to keep it holy.' <em>Zachor</em> (H2142, remember): the covenantal memory-word — remember is not a passive mental recollection but an active bringing-into-the-present (as in YHWH remembering the covenant in Exod 2:24). <em>Lekadsho</em> (to sanctify/set it apart): the Sabbath's holiness is not intrinsic to the day but given by covenantal act — the same sanctification word used for Sinai (v.8-10). Time is made holy by separation and divine assignment, just as space is made holy.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>sheshet yamim ta'avod ve'asita kol-melachtecha</strong>: 'Six days you shall labor and do all your work.' The positive command precedes the prohibition: six days of productive work are commanded before the seventh of rest. The Sabbath is not the negation of labor but its covenantal framing: human creativity and productivity are honored in six days; the seventh day declares that human work is embedded in a larger divine rhythm and does not define existence. Work receives its meaning from the rest that frames it.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>veyom hashvii Shabbat laYHWH Eloheicha lo ta'aseh khol-melacha atah uvinkha uvitecha avdecha va'amatcha uvhemtecha</strong>: 'But the seventh day is a Sabbath to YHWH your God. You shall not do any work, you or your son or your daughter, your servant or your maidservant, your livestock, or the stranger within your gates.' The comprehensive scope of the Sabbath rest extends to every level of the social hierarchy: children, servants, animals, foreigners — the Sabbath creates a covenantal equality of rest. Even the animals and the alien resident participate in the covenant's rhythm of rest. No social hierarchy survives the Sabbath day.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>ki sheshet yamim asah YHWH et-hashamayim ve'et-ha'aretz vayinafash</strong> (<em>kî šēšet-yāmîm ʿāśāh Yhwh ʾet-haššāmayim wĕʾet-hāʾāreṣ wayyinnāpaš</em>): 'For in six days YHWH made the heavens and earth, and rested (<em>nefesh</em>) on the seventh day.' <em>Vayinafash</em> (H5314): from <em>nefesh</em> (soul/breath/life) — YHWH breathed/refreshed/took breath. The anthropomorphic language is striking: YHWH's rest on the seventh day is described as the refreshment of a living being. Human Sabbath rest participates in the divine rest-pattern embedded in creation — the weekly rhythm is cosmologically grounded, not merely socially convenient.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>kabed et-avicha ve'et-imecha</strong> (<em>kabbēd ʾet-ʾābîkā wĕʾet-ʾimmekā</em>): 'Honor your father and your mother.' <em>Kabed</em> (H3513, honor/be heavy): from the root meaning heavy/weighty — to honor is to give weight to, to treat as consequential. The commandment grounds social order in the family: the first four commandments address the vertical relationship (Israel to YHWH); this commandment transitions to the horizontal (Israelite to Israelite) by beginning with the foundational human relationship. The promise attached — that your days may be long in the land — ties individual obedience to national covenantal blessing.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>lo tirtzach</strong> (<em>lōʾ tirṣāḥ</em>): 'You shall not murder.' <em>Ratzach</em> (H7523, murder): specifically premeditated, willful killing — not the same as <em>harag</em> (H2026, kill generally) or <em>hemit</em> (H4191, put to death). The commandment prohibits intentional, unauthorized taking of human life — a prohibition grounded in the image of God (Gen 9:6: whoever sheds the blood of man, by man shall his blood be shed, for God made man in his own image). Human life is inviolable because the image of God makes each person a representative of the Creator.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>lo tin'af</strong> (<em>lōʾ tinʾāp</em>): 'You shall not commit adultery.' <em>Na'af</em> (H5003, commit adultery): the sexual corollary of the first commandment's covenant-loyalty requirement. Marriage is the human covenant that structurally mirrors the divine covenant; adultery is the human betrayal that structurally mirrors idolatry. The prophets consistently use adultery as the metaphor for Israel's covenant-breaking (Jer 3:8; Ezek 16; Hos 1-3). The prohibition protects both the marriage covenant and the community's covenantal integrity.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>lo tignov</strong> (<em>lōʾ tiganob</em>): 'You shall not steal.' <em>Ganav</em> (H1589, steal): the taking of what belongs to another — whether property, persons (kidnapping is also covered under this root, Exod 21:16), or anything belonging to another. Respect for the neighbor's possessions is grounded in respect for the neighbor as a fellow covenant member with God-given rights. The command extends the image-of-God protection from life (v.13) to dignity (v.14) to property (v.15).</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>lo ta'aneh vere'acha ed shav</strong> (<em>lōʾ-taʿăneh bĕrēʿăkā ʿēd šāwĕʾ</em>): 'You shall not testify against your neighbor as a false witness.' <em>Ed shav</em> (witness of emptiness/vanity): <em>shav</em> is the same word as in v.7 — the emptiness that misuses the divine name is the same emptiness that perverts testimony. The legal system depends on truthful testimony; false witness destroys the possibility of justice. The commandment protects the covenantal community's capacity to adjudicate rightly — the court as the arena of covenant justice.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>lo tachmod beit re'echa lo tachmod eshet re'echa ve'avdo va'amato veshoro vachamoro</strong> (<em>lōʾ taḥmōd bêt rēʿăkā lōʾ taḥmōd ʾēšet rēʿăkā wĕʿaḇdô wăʾămāṯô wĕšôrô waḥămōrô</em>): 'You shall not covet your neighbor's house. You shall not covet your neighbor's wife or his servant or his maidservant or his ox or his donkey or anything that belongs to your neighbor.' <em>Chamad</em> (H2530, covet/desire intensely): the desire for what belongs to another, named for the attractive pull it exerts. Unique among the commandments in targeting inner desire rather than external action — the only commandment that can only be violated before the act. Paul cites this commandment as the one that awakened his awareness of sin (Rom 7:7: I would not have known covetousness if the law had not said, you shall not covet).</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>vekhol-ha'am ro'im et-haqolot ve'et-halappidim ve'et qol hashofar ve'et-hahar ashen vayar ha'am vayanu'u vaya'amdu merachok</strong>: 'All the people saw the thunderings and the flashes and the sound of the trumpet and the mountain smoking. When the people saw it, they trembled and stood far off.' The synesthetic description — seeing thunder and lightning, the visible and audible blended — is the phenomenology of theophany. The people's trembling response and their standing far off is the appropriate creaturely response to unconditioned divine presence.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>vayomeru el-Mosheh daber-atah imanu venishma'ah ve'al-yedaber imanu Elohim pen-namut</strong>: 'They said to Moses: You speak to us and we will listen, but let not God speak to us lest we die.' The people's request for a human mediator is not disobedience but honest self-knowledge: they cannot sustain the direct encounter with YHWH. Their fear validates the necessity of the Mosaic mediatorial office. The pattern repeats: Israel needs a mediator between YHWH's holiness and their creaturely limitation. Moses is the type; Christ is the antitype — the one mediator between God and humanity (1 Tim 2:5) who resolves the mediatorial need permanently.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vayomer Mosheh el-ha'am al-tira'u ki livliti nassot etchem ba ha'Elohim uvavur tihyeh yirato al-peneichem</strong>: 'Moses said to the people: Do not be afraid, for God has come to test you, that the fear of him may be before you, that you may not sin.' The purpose of the theophanic terror: <em>livliti nassot etchem</em> (to test you) and <em>yirato al-peneichem</em> (his fear before your face). The terrifying encounter is not punishment but pedagogy — the fear generated is the appropriate orientation toward YHWH that prevents sin. The theology of fear and trembling (Phil 2:12 — work out your salvation with fear and trembling) is rooted in this Sinai principle.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vaya'amod ha'am merachok veMosheh nigash el-ha'arafel</strong>: 'The people stood far off, and Moses drew near to the thick darkness where God was.' <em>Arafel</em> (H6205, thick darkness/deep darkness): the darkness that surrounds the divine light — not the absence of YHWH but his concealment within an overwhelming cloud. The people stand far off; Moses enters the darkness alone. The covenant mediator goes where the people cannot follow — into the thick of divine presence. Hebrews uses this pattern: Christ entered not a human sanctuary but heaven itself (Heb 9:24), the true most holy place where we cannot go except through him.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>vayomer YHWH el-Mosheh ko tomar el-bnei Yisrael atem re'item ki min-hashamayim dibarti imachem</strong>: 'YHWH said to Moses: Thus you shall say to the children of Israel: You yourselves have seen that I have spoken with you from heaven.' The direct appeal to witnessed experience: <em>atem re'item</em> (you yourselves have seen). The covenant is grounded not in tradition alone but in the community's own witnessed encounter with the divine voice. The appeal to testimony-based faith is the OT foundation for the NT's eyewitness theology (1 John 1:1-3: what we have seen and heard we proclaim to you).</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>lo ta'asun iti elohei kesef ve'elohei zahav lo ta'asun lachem</strong>: 'You shall not make alongside me gods of silver and of gold; you shall not make such for yourselves.' The prohibition immediately follows the theophany — the community that has just heard YHWH's voice directly is immediately warned against the idol-substitute. The golden calf (Exod 32) will violate this commandment within weeks. The speed of Israel's violation underscores the commandment's necessity: human inclination toward tangible gods is powerful and persistent.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>mizbach adamah ta'aseh li vezavachta alav et-oloteicha ve'et-shlameicha et-tsoncha ve'et-beqarecha</strong>: 'An altar of earth you shall make for me and sacrifice on it your burnt offerings and peace offerings, your sheep and your oxen.' The simple altar permitted after the Decalogue — earth or unhewn stone (v.25) — sets the minimalist principle for early Israelite worship: the altar's simplicity declares YHWH's sufficiency. No human craftsmanship adorns the first altar; the only material is what the earth already provides. The elaborate tabernacle and temple are later, more specific instructions; this is the baseline.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>ve'im-mizbach avanim ta'aseh-li lo-tivneh ethen gazit ki charbecha haneifta aleiha vatechaleleiha</strong>: 'And if you make me a stone altar, you shall not build it of cut stones, for if you wield your tool on it you profane it.' The prohibition of dressed stone for the altar: human tool-work profanes the altar — the natural, uncut stone preserves its integrity. The rationale is contested (the stones' natural completeness, or the avoidance of phallic symbols carved on stones). The principle: human craftsmanship is not required to make the altar acceptable to YHWH; what YHWH provides is sufficient for approach to him.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>velo ta'aleh bema'alot al-mizbechi asher lo-tigaleh ervatecha alav</strong>: 'You shall not go up by steps to my altar so that your nakedness is not uncovered on it.' The altar's access must not involve raised stairs that expose the priest's nakedness — a combination of modesty requirement and anti-Canaanite contrast (Canaanite altar worship involved fertility rites). The practical regulation shapes the covenantal aesthetics of worship: the holy space requires an approach that maintains the dignity and integrity of those who serve in it.</p>"
},
"21": {
"1": "<p><strong>ve'eleh hamishpatim asher tasim lifneihem</strong> (<em>wĕʾēlleh hammiŝpāṭîm ʾăšer tāśîm lipnêhem</em>): 'And these are the ordinances/judgments you shall set before them.' <em>Mishpatim</em> (H4941, judgments/ordinances): from <em>shafat</em> (H8199, judge/govern) — these are the legal applications of the Decalogue's principles. The Book of the Covenant (Exod 21-23) is the first legal code given to Israel, covering concrete cases. <em>Tasim lifneihem</em> (place before them): the same verb used for placing food before guests and for presenting arguments in court — the laws are set out for the community's engagement, not merely decreed from above.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>ki tiqneh eved ivri shesh shanim ya'avod uvashvii yetse laChofshi chinam</strong>: 'When you buy a Hebrew slave, he shall serve six years, and in the seventh he shall go free, for nothing.' The debt-slavery law applies the Sabbath principle to servitude: six years of service; the seventh is freedom. The same seven-year structure (shemitah, the sabbatical year) governs land use (Lev 25:1-7) and debt release (Deut 15:1-11). The Sabbath pattern extends across all dimensions of Israelite life: work and rest, land and fallow, slavery and freedom.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>im-begapo yavo begapo yetse im-ba'al-isha hu veyatsa ishto imo</strong>: 'If he came in single, he shall go out single; if he came in married, his wife shall go out with him.' The law preserves the integrity of pre-existing family bonds: the master who receives a slave with a wife cannot dissolve the marriage. The slave's domestic relationships are not extinguished by his servitude — a fundamental acknowledgment of the slave's personhood beyond his economic function.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>im-adonav yiten lo isha veyalda lo banim o vanot ha'isha veyeladeha tihyeh la'adoneiha vehu yetse vegapo</strong>: 'If his master gives him a wife and she bears him sons or daughters, the wife and her children shall be her master's, and he shall go out alone.' The hard case: a master-arranged marriage produces children who belong to the master. The tension between the slave's freedom and his family creates the scenario of v.5-6 — the voluntary permanent slavery. The law acknowledges the painful cost of freedom: some bonds exceed the value of liberty.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>ve'im-amor yomar ha'eved ahavti et-adoni et-ishti ve'et-banai lo etse chofshi</strong>: 'But if the slave plainly says: I love my master, my wife, and my children; I will not go free.' <em>Ahavareti et-adoni</em> (I love my master): love as the motive for voluntary permanent slavery — the unusual circumstance where a freed person chooses permanent servitude out of love. Psalm 40:6-8 (LXX: a body you prepared for me; in the scroll it is written of me — I delight to do your will, O God) applies this exact law typologically to Christ: the one who could go free (pre-incarnate) chose permanent embodied servitude out of love. Hebrews 10:5-7 cites the Psalm as the Servant's own words.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>vehigio adonav el-ha'Elohim vehigio el-hadelet o el-hamezuzah vertza adonav et-ozno bamartze va'avado le'olam</strong>: 'His master shall bring him to God, and he shall bring him to the door or doorpost. His master shall pierce his ear with an awl, and he shall be his slave forever.' The ear pierced at the doorpost: the doorpost is the location of the Passover blood (Exod 12:7, 22-23) and of the mezuzah (Deut 6:9). The ear attached to the doorpost makes the body physically connected to the house — the voluntary permanent slave is bound by his own body to the place of covenant. <em>Le'olam</em> (forever/to the age): permanent belonging through love-chosen submission.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>vechi-yimkor ish et-bito le'amah lo tetse ketset ha'avadim</strong>: 'When a man sells his daughter as a maidservant, she shall not go out as male servants do.' The special provisions for female debt-slaves acknowledge the additional vulnerability of women in servitude — her exit conditions are different from male slaves. The law is not a license for the sale of daughters but a regulation that limits exploitation within a practice already embedded in the ancient economy.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>im-ra'ah be'einei adoneiha asher-lo yo'adah vefadah le'am nachri lo-yimshol limkoraha bibegdo-vah</strong>: 'If she does not please her master who designated her for himself, he shall let her be redeemed. He has no right to sell her to a foreign people, since he has dealt faithlessly with her.' The protection against exploitation: if a master fails to fulfill his obligations toward a designated slave-wife, he loses the right to sell her. <em>Bigdo vah</em> (dealing faithlessly with her) — the same root as <em>beged</em> (treachery/garment-deceit) in covenant language. The slave has rights; the master cannot simply dispose of her.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>ve'im-livno yi'adennah kemishpat habanot ya'aseh-lah</strong>: 'If he designates her for his son, he shall treat her as a daughter.' The full daughter-status for the slave-wife given to the master's son — she is integrated into the family with full family rights. The law consistently moves toward humanization and integration rather than mere regulation of exploitation.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>im-acheret yiqach-lo she'erah kesutah ve'onatah lo yigra</strong>: 'If he takes another wife to himself, he shall not diminish her food, her clothing, or her marital rights.' The three inviolable rights of the first wife when a second is taken: food, clothing, and conjugal rights (<em>onah</em>, H5772). Even within a polygynous arrangement, the law protects the first wife's basic claims. Marital obligation is a legal minimum that cannot be reduced by preference for a newer wife.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>ve'im-shlosh-eleh lo ya'aseh-lah veyatsa chinam ein kasef</strong>: 'If he does not do these three things for her, she shall go out for nothing, without payment of money.' The slave-wife's exit right when the master defaults on his obligations: she is free, without cost to her. The law creates accountability for the master who makes covenantal commitments — failure to fulfill the three obligations transfers freedom back to the woman. Covenant obligations are enforceable even for the powerless.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>makeh ish vamet mot yumat</strong>: 'Whoever strikes a man so that he dies shall be put to death.' The homicide law establishes capital punishment for intentional killing — grounded in Gen 9:6 (whoever sheds the blood of man, by man shall his blood be shed). The death-penalty for murder is not a societal deterrent but a covenantal response to the violation of the image of God in the victim: the killer has assaulted the image of YHWH and must answer with his own life.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>va'asher lo tzadah veha'Elohim inah leyado vesamti lecha makom asher yanus shamah</strong>: 'But if he did not lie in wait, God delivered him into his hand — I will appoint you a place where he may flee.' The unintentional manslayer law introduces the concept of divine causation in accidental death: <em>ha'Elohim inah leyado</em> (God caused it to come into his hand). Accidental death occurs within divine providence, not outside it. The cities of refuge (Num 35:6-34) implement this provision — a place of safety for those who kill without intent. The distinction between intent and accident is foundational to biblical jurisprudence.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>ve'chi-yazid ish al-re'ehu lehargo vetormah mizbechi tikachenu lamut</strong>: 'But if a man willfully attacks another to kill him by cunning, you shall take him from my altar that he may die.' <em>Betormah</em> (with treachery/cunning): the premeditated murder that uses deception. Even the altar provides no sanctuary for the deliberate murderer — YHWH's house is not a loophole for covenant-breakers. The contrast with the accidental manslayer (who finds asylum) is sharp: motive determines the application of the law.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>umakeh aviv ve'imo mot yumat</strong>: 'Whoever strikes his father or mother shall be put to death.' The capital extension of the fifth commandment's honor-principle: physical assault on parents is the extreme violation of the honor-commandment, treated as seriously as murder. The family is the foundational covenant unit; its destruction from within through violence against parents is equivalent to the destruction of the covenant community itself.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>veganev ish umechrahu venimatze veyado mot yumat</strong>: 'Whoever steals a man and sells him, if he is found in his possession, shall be put to death.' The kidnapping-for-slavery law: the selling of a free person into slavery is a capital offense — the theft of a person, the most fundamental of thefts. Paul cites this law in 1 Tim 1:10 (enslavers/kidnappers as lawbreakers). The prohibition on person-theft places the biblical tradition in fundamental opposition to chattel slavery as a system.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>umeqalel aviv ve'imo mot yumat</strong>: 'Whoever curses his father or mother shall be put to death.' <em>Qalel</em> (H7043, curse/treat with contempt/make light): the opposite of <em>kabed</em> (honor). To curse parents is to treat them as worthless — the maximum violation of the fifth commandment. The law creates a symmetry: the death-penalty for striking (v.15) and for cursing (v.17) parents brackets all forms of parental assault. Jesus cites this law in Mark 7:10 to expose the Pharisees' Corban loophole as a violation of the commandment.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>vechi-yarivu anashim vehikah ish et-re'ehu be'even o ve'egrof velo yamut venafal lemishkav</strong>: 'When men quarrel and one strikes the other with a stone or with his fist and the man does not die but takes to his bed.' The personal injury law distinguishes between assault that kills and assault that incapacitates. The graduated liability structure — full compensation for lost time plus medical care (v.19) but not capital punishment — shows that the law tracks actual harm rather than applying blanket penalties.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>im-yaqum vehithalek bachutz al-mishantoh veniqah hamakeh raq shivto yiten virappo yerap'e</strong>: 'If the victim rises and walks outdoors with his staff, the one who struck him shall be clear; only he shall pay for the loss of his time and shall have him thoroughly healed.' <em>Verapo yerap'e</em> (shall thoroughly heal): infinitive absolute — he shall see to complete healing. The assailant bears both the economic loss (lost wages) and the full medical cost. The double responsibility of economic and medical restitution is the legal embodiment of neighbor-love: the one who caused harm must bear its full cost.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vechi-yakeh ish et-avdo o et-amato baShevet vamet tachat yado naqom yinaqem</strong>: 'When a man strikes his slave or female slave with a rod and the slave dies under his hand, he shall be avenged.' The master's capital liability for killing a slave: <em>naqom yinaqem</em> (he shall be avenged/punished). The precise punishment is debated, but the principle is clear — the slave's life has legal standing. The slave is not simply the master's property to kill at will; the slave's life creates covenantal accountability for the master.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>ach im-yom o yomayim ya'amod lo yinaqem ki caspo hu</strong>: 'But if the slave survives a day or two, he is not to be avenged, for the slave is his money.' The provision for a slave who lingers after assault and then dies: the delay is taken as evidence that death was not the intent (Mesopotamian law codes contain similar provisions). The phrase <em>ki caspo hu</em> (for he is his money/property) is ethically uncomfortable but legally realistic: the master's economic self-interest presumably argues against murdering his own slave.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>vechi-yinatzu anashim venagfu isha harah veyatze'u yeladeiha velo yihyeh ason</strong>: 'When men strive and strike a pregnant woman, and her children come out but there is no harm.' The case of miscarriage caused by bystander injury — establishing legal liability for injury to a pregnant woman. <em>Velo yihyeh ason</em> (no further harm/disaster): if the woman and child are not further harmed, a fine is imposed. The legal protection of the pregnant woman extends to the pregnancy itself.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>ve'im ason yihyeh venatata nefesh tachat nafesh</strong> (<em>wĕʾim-ʾāsôn yihyeh wĕnātattāh nāpeš taḥat nāpeš</em>): 'But if there is harm, then you shall pay life for life.' <em>Nefesh tachat nefesh</em> (life for life): the <em>lex talionis</em> — the principle of proportional justice. The law is not a license for personal vengeance but a limit on it: the response must be proportional to the injury, no more. The lex talionis protects the accused from disproportionate punishment by legally capping the penalty at equivalence. Jesus's teaching on turning the other cheek (Matt 5:38-39) is not the abolition of just legal claims but the transformation of the personal response to injury.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>ayin tachat ayin shen tachat shen yad tachat yad regel tachat ragel</strong>: 'Eye for eye, tooth for tooth, hand for hand, foot for foot.' The fourfold list of specific equivalences makes the proportionality principle concrete. In most ancient Near Eastern legal contexts, the lex talionis applied literally only in theory; in practice, monetary compensation was accepted. The Mishnah (Bava Qamma 8:1) interprets the law as requiring monetary compensation. The principle is justice, not physical retaliation for its own sake.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>kevi'ah tachat kevi'ah petza tachat patza chaburah tachat chaburah</strong>: 'Burn for burn, wound for wound, stripe for stripe.' The extension of the lex talionis to injuries less than loss of limb: burns, wounds, bruises. The principle of proportional equivalence covers the full spectrum of bodily injury. The comprehensive list — from life (v.23) to eye/tooth/hand/foot (v.24) to burns/wounds/stripes (v.25) — ensures that every level of harm has a proportional legal response.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>vechi-yakeh ish et-ein avdo o et-ein amato veshichetah lachofshi yeshalachenu tachat eino</strong>: 'When a man strikes the eye of his slave, male or female, and destroys it, he shall let the slave go free because of his eye.' The eye-for-eye principle applied to slave-injury produces not physical equivalence but freedom: the master who permanently injures his slave's eye loses ownership. The lex talionis in the slave-injury context (v.26-27) functions as a liberation principle — injury to the eye or tooth of a slave purchases freedom.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>ve'im-shen avdo o shen amato yapil lachofshi yeshalachenu tachat shino</strong>: 'If he knocks out the tooth of his slave, male or female, he shall let the slave go free for his tooth's sake.' The tooth-for-tooth principle applied to slaves: a knocked-out tooth purchases freedom. Even the smallest permanent injury to a slave (teeth are the smallest body part specifically mentioned in the lex talionis) triggers the freedom clause. The slave's bodily integrity creates a legal claim on freedom — the most radical expression of the Israelite slave-protection laws.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>vechi-yigach shor et-ish o et-isha vamet saqol yisaqel hashor velo ye'achel et-besaro uva'al hashor naqui</strong>: 'When an ox gores a man or woman to death, the ox shall be stoned, and its flesh shall not be eaten, but the owner of the ox shall be free of liability.' The ox-goring law: the ox is executed (stoning, the same death as for human murderers — reflecting the seriousness of life taken) but the owner bears no liability in the first instance. The law presupposes that an animal's behavior is not foreseeable without prior notice.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>ve'im shor nagach hu mitmol shilshom vehu'ad bibe'alav velo yishmerenu vaheimit ish o isha hashor yisaqel vegam-be'alav yumat</strong>: 'But if the ox had a habit of goring in the past, and its owner has been warned but did not keep it in, and it kills a man or woman, the ox shall be stoned, and its owner also shall be put to death.' The ox with a known goring habit: the owner who receives warning and does not restrain his dangerous animal bears capital liability when the animal kills. Foreseeable harm creates culpability — the principle that establishes negligence as a legal category.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>im-kofer yushat alav venat'a pidon nafsho kechol asher yushat alav</strong>: 'If a ransom is imposed on him, then he shall give for the redemption of his life whatever is imposed on him.' The ransom alternative to capital punishment for the negligent ox-owner: <em>kofer</em> (H3724, ransom/redemption price). The <em>kofer</em> is the substitutionary payment that redeems a forfeited life — the same root as the Day of Atonement's <em>kippur</em> (Lev 16) and the substitutionary animal sacrifice. The legal ransom principle illuminates the theological atonement vocabulary: a life at risk is redeemed by payment of a price.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>o-ven yigach o-bat yigach kemishpat hazeh ye'aseh lo</strong>: 'Whether it gores a son or gores a daughter, the same rule applies to him.' The equality principle: the law applies uniformly regardless of the victim's age or gender. Legal protections are not differentiated by the social status of the victim — a daughter's life and a son's life are legally equivalent claims on the same standard of justice.</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>im-eved yigach hashor o amah kesef shloshim shaqalim yiten la'adonav vehashor yisaqel</strong>: 'If the ox gores a slave, male or female, the owner shall pay thirty shekels of silver to their master, and the ox shall be stoned.' Thirty shekels of silver: the legal value of a slave's life. This is the same amount paid to Judas for betraying Jesus (Matt 26:15; 27:9-10) — Zechariah's price of a slave (Zech 11:12-13). The number connecting the slave-valuation law to the betrayal price is the gospel's most concentrated use of the lex talionis: Christ's life valued as a slave's ransom precisely so that he might be the ransom for many (Mark 10:45).</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>vechi-yiftach ish bor o ki-yichre ish bor velo yechasennu venaphal shamah shor o chamor</strong>: 'When a man opens a pit, or when a man digs a pit and does not cover it, and an ox or donkey falls into it.' The pit-hazard law: liability for the uncovered pit extends to any animal that falls in. The law requires proactive hazard management — not merely avoiding direct injury but taking responsibility for dangerous conditions one creates. The duty of care extends beyond direct action to the foreseeable consequences of one's omissions.</p>",
"34": "<p><strong>ba'al habor yeshallem kesef yashiv livnehem vehamet yihyeh-lo</strong>: 'The owner of the pit shall make restitution; he shall give money to its owner, and the dead animal shall be his.' The restitution principle: full market value owed for the lost animal, with the owner receiving the carcass. The economic calculus of damage-and-restitution establishes that the party who created the hazard bears the full cost of the harm it causes.</p>",
"35": "<p><strong>vechi-yigof shor ish et-shor re'ehu vamet umakeru et-hashor hachai vechalelu et-kaspo vesat hachama hameit yechetzun</strong>: 'When one man's ox injures another's ox and it dies, they shall sell the live ox and share its price, and the dead animal they shall also share.' The civil liability for animal-on-animal harm: the loss is shared equally between the owner of the injuring animal and the owner of the injured animal — a default risk-sharing principle when neither owner is negligent.</p>",
"36": "<p><strong>o noda ki nagach hashor mitmol shilshom velo yishmerenu be'alav shalem yeshalem shor tachat hashor vehamet yihyeh-lo</strong>: 'Or if it is known that the ox had a habit of goring in the past and its owner did not keep it in, he shall repay ox for ox, and the dead ox shall be his.' The known-danger negligence case in animal injury: full liability when prior goring established foreseeability. The law closes with the principle that prior knowledge creates full responsibility — the same principle underlying the warnings about the consequences of covenant violation that YHWH gives throughout the Torah. Knowledge of the law creates accountability under it.</p>"
}
}

existing = load_comm("mkt-original", "exodus")
merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
save_comm("mkt-original", "exodus", existing)

# Verify
interlinear = json.loads((ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / 'exodus.json').read_text())
all_ok = True
for ch, desc in [("19", "25"), ("20", "26"), ("21", "36")]:
    have = len(existing.get(ch, {}))
    total = len(interlinear.get(ch, {}))
    missing = set(interlinear.get(ch, {}).keys()) - set(existing.get(ch, {}).keys())
    if missing:
        print(f"ch {ch}: MISSING {sorted(missing, key=int)}")
        all_ok = False
    else:
        print(f"ch {ch}: complete ({have} verses)")

if all_ok:
    print("All verses present")
